  "text": "The configuration loading pipeline in Grafana centers on four files:\n\n1. **pkg/setting/setting.go** \u2014 The core configuration engine. `Cfg.Load()` (line 1138) orchestrates everything: it calls `loadConfiguration()` (line 963) which loads `conf/defaults.ini` via `ini.Load()`, applies command-line default properties, loads user-specified config files via `loadSpecifiedConfigFile()` (line 922), applies environment variable overrides via `applyEnvVariableOverrides()` (line 744) which uses `EnvKey()` (line 855) to construct GF_SECTION_KEY patterns and `os.Getenv()`, and then calls `expandConfig()`. After loading, `parseINIFile()` (line 1165) reads default values per section (server, security, paths, etc.) using `valueAsString()`. `RedactedValue()` (line 660) masks sensitive config values matching patterns like PASSWORD, SECRET, PRIVATE_KEY, etc.\n\n2. **pkg/setting/expanders.go** \u2014 Implements `expandConfig()` which expands `${}` and `$__env{}` / `$__file{}` variable references in INI values, including environment variable expansion via `envExpander`.\n\n3. **pkg/setting/provider.go** \u2014 Defines the `Provider` interface and `OSSImpl` which exposes configuration to the API layer. `OSSImpl.Current()` (line 118) iterates all INI sections and applies `RedactedValue()` to every key, producing a `SettingsBag` with sensitive values masked.\n\n4. **pkg/api/admin.go** \u2014 Implements the `/api/admin/settings` endpoint via `AdminGetSettings()` (line 29) which calls `SettingsProvider.Current()` to get the already-redacted settings bag, then filters by access control permissions via `getAuthorizedSettings()`.",
